## Setter Injection in Spring

---

### 🧠 Concept First

In **Setter Injection**, Spring injects the dependency by calling the **setter method** of the class after creating the object via the default (no-arg) constructor.

```
Spring does this internally:
1. Student s = new Student();        // no-arg constructor
2. s.setName("Nivas");               // setter called by Spring
```

---

### 📦 Example — Without Spring (tight coupling)

```java
class Student {
    private String name;
    private int age;

    public void setName(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public void setAge(int age) {
        this.age = age;
    }

    public void show() {
        System.out.println(name + " - " + age);
    }
}

// Main
Student s = new Student();
s.setName("Nivas");
s.setAge(21);
s.show();
```

You're manually calling setters — **tight coupling**, Spring not involved.

---

### ✅ With Spring — Setter Injection via XML

#### Step 1 — Student.java
```java
package com.example;

public class Student {

    private String name;
    private int age;

    // No-arg constructor (Spring needs this)
    public Student() {}

    // Setters
    public void setName(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public void setAge(int age) {
        this.age = age;
    }

    public void show() {
        System.out.println("Name: " + name + ", Age: " + age);
    }
}
```

---

#### Step 2 — beans.xml (Spring config)

```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<beans xmlns="http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans"
       xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
       xsi:schemaLocation="
         http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans
         http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans/spring-beans.xsd">

    <bean id="student" class="com.example.Student">
        <!-- Setter Injection using <property> tag -->
        <property name="name" value="Nivas"/>
        <property name="age"  value="21"/>
    </bean>

</beans>
```

> `name="name"` → Spring calls `setName()`  
> `name="age"` → Spring calls `setAge()`  
> The `name` attribute must **match the setter method name** (minus "set", lowercase first letter)

---

#### Step 3 — Main.java

```java
import org.springframework.context.ApplicationContext;
import org.springframework.context.support.ClassPathXmlApplicationContext;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        ApplicationContext ctx =
            new ClassPathXmlApplicationContext("beans.xml");

        Student s = (Student) ctx.getBean("student");
        s.show();
        // Output: Name: Nivas, Age: 21
    }
}
```

